Sure! Here's an example code for a Flutter page that allows the user to search a database of "cards":

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class CardSearchPage extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _CardSearchPageState createState() => _CardSearchPageState();
}

class _CardSearchPageState extends State<CardSearchPage> {
  String _searchQuery = '';

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Card Search'),
        centerTitle: true,
      ),
      body: Column(
        children: [
          Padding(
            padding: const EdgeInsets.all(16.0),
            child: TextField(
              decoration: InputDecoration(
                hintText: 'Search for a card...',
                prefixIcon: Icon(Icons.search),
              ),
              onChanged: (value) {
                setState(() {
                  _searchQuery = value.toLowerCase();
                });
              },
            ),
          ),
          Expanded(
            child: ListView.builder(
              itemCount: cards.length,
              itemBuilder: (context, index) {
                final card = cards[index];
                if (_searchQuery.isNotEmpty &&
                    !card.title.toLowerCase().contains(_searchQuery)) {
                  return SizedBox.shrink();
                }
                return ListTile(
                  title: Text(card.title),
                  onTap: () {
                    // Navigate to card details page
                  },
                );
              },
            ),
          ),
          Padding(
            padding: const EdgeInsets.all(16.0),
            child: ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () {
                // Navigate to random card details page
              },
              child: Text('Random Card'),
            ),
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}

class Card {
  final String title;
  final String description;

  Card({required this.title, required this.description});
}

final List<Card> cards = [
  Card(
      title: 'Card 1',
      description: 'This is the description for card 1.'),
  Card(
      title: 'Card 2',
      description: 'This is the description for card 2.'),
  Card(
      title: 'Card 3',
      description: 'This is the description for card 3.'),
];
```

In this example, the page consists of an `AppBar`, a search box `TextField`, a `ListView` of cards that are filtered based on the search query, and a button that takes the user to a random card. The `Card` class is just a simple data class that holds the card's `title` and `description`.

To filter the cards based on the search query, we use the `ListView.builder`'s `itemBuilder` callback to check whether each card's `title` contains the search query. If it doesn't, we return a `SizedBox.shrink()` widget, which has zero height and width and effectively removes the card from the list. If the search query is empty or the card's title contains the search query, we return a `ListTile` widget that displays the card's `title`.

To handle navigating to the card details page or the random card details page, you can use the `Navigator.push` method and pass in the appropriate `Route`.
